        cons: ['It is strictly a B2B API infrastructure product; a casual student wanting to furiously transcribe an hour-long class lecture through a beautiful web dashboard is fundamentally not the target audience (they should use standard Rev.com or Otter.ai)', 'While terrifyingly accurate, an AI is ultimately a mathematical model; if used for high-stakes medical or complex legal environments, an unedited 2% error rate can still result in catastrophic misinterpretations if a human doesn\'t review the output', 'Hosting massive computing pipelines requires relying heavily on external cloud infrastructure; if the user possesses highly classified military intelligence audio, they cannot logically send that data over the internet to Rev\'s cloud servers', 'The pricing structure operates on relentless scale; while cheap per minute, an enterprise processing 10,000 hours of audio a month is incurring a massive recurring software integration cost'],
        pricing_overview: '<p>Rev.ai operations on a brutal, strictly metered, "Pay-As-You-Go" Developer pricing model. Pricing is fundamentally calculated "Per Minute of Audio Processed." Standard asynchronous transcription is incredibly cheap. Demanding live, low-latency streaming transcription or utilizing complex topic-extraction AI layers incurs slight fractional cost increases. Massive enterprise deployments rely on aggressively negotiated tiers based on promised volume commitments.</p>',
